'''Folarin Jerry Balogun''' ({{Audio|Folarin_Jerry_Balogun.wav|listen}}; born July 3, 2001) is a <!-- do not include 'American' per talk page -->professional [[association football|soccer]] player who plays as a [[Striker (association football)|striker]] for {{French football updater|Monaco}} club [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] and the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]].

A [[Arsenal F.C. Under-21s and Academy|Hale End]] academy prospect of [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], Balogun was promoted to the first team in 2020 and featured sparingly for the club, later going on loan to [[EFL Championship]] side [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] in 2022. In the following season, Balogun made his breakthrough in a loan to [[Ligue 1]] side [[Reims FC|Reims]], where he scored 22 goals in [[2022-23 Stade de Reims season|his one season]]; the highest ever for an American in a [[Big Five (association football)|top five European league]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=USMNT REWIND: Folarin Balogun Becomes First U.S. International to Score 20 Goals in a Top-Five European League {{!}} U.S. Soccer Official Website |url=https://ussoccer.com/stories/2023/05/usmnt-rewind-balogun-becomes-first-us-international-to-score-20-goals-in-a-top-five-european-league |access-date=May 30, 2026 |website=ussoccer.com |language=en}}</ref> In August 2023, Balogun left Arsenal and signed with [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] for €40 million ($43 million), where he was named the [[2025–26 AS Monaco FC season|2025–26]] Monaco Player of the Season.<ref>{{cite web |date=September 1, 2023 |title=Why did Arsenal agree to sell USMNT star Folarin Balogun? Mikel Arteta explains €40m transfer to Monaco |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/lists/why-arsenal-sell-usmnt-star-folarin-balogun-mikel-arteta-explains-40m-transfer-monaco/blt209df551351e8905 |access-date=November 1, 2023 |website=Goal.com}}</ref>

Balogun represented both the United States and England at the youth international level. In May 2023, he decided to play for the United States senior national team. He made his debut in June 2023, winning the [[2022–23 CONCACAF Nations League|2023 CONCACAF Nations League]] and scoring his first goal in the [[2023 CONCACAF Nations League final|final]].<ref name=":1" />

== Early life ==
Balogun was born in [[Brooklyn]], New York to Nigerian parents.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Chédeville |first=Damien |date=August 31, 2023 |title=All you need to know about Folarin Balogun |url=https://www.asmonaco.com/en/need-to-know-folarin-balogun/ |access-date=November 20, 2025 |website=AS Monaco |language=en-US}}</ref> He moved to the [[United Kingdom]] with his parents when he was one month old,<ref>{{cite news |title=Mikel Arteta sends message to Arsenal contract rebel Folarin Balogun |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/10/30/mikel-arteta-sends-message-to-arsenal-contract-rebel-folarin-balogun-13505305/ |access-date=November 3, 2020 |work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=October 30, 2020 |location=[[London]]}}</ref> growing up in [[London]], England.<ref name="ESPN2018">{{cite news |last1=Karen |first1=Mattias |title=U.S. under-18s call up promising Arsenal prospect Folarin Balogun |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/arsenal/story/3605487/us-under-18s-call-up-promising-arsenal-prospect-folarin-balogun |access-date=November 3, 2020 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=August 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Halloran |first1=Connor |date=October 12, 2023 |title=Folarin Balogun's winding, fateful path to Monaco and USMNT |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/38640119/folarin-balogun-usmnt-monaco-arsenal-reims |access-date=September 15, 2025 |website=ESPN}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Arsenal===
====Early career====
Balogun joined [[Arsenal F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Arsenal]] at the age of eight, after being scouted while playing for his previous Sunday League side, Aldersbrook.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/arsenal-academy-update-smith-rowe-balogun-set-for/qu2ix5ne8n0i1cq2j6ulpyfvw|title=Arsenal academy update: Smith-Rowe, Willock & Balogun set for breakthrough campaign|first=Chris|last=Wheatley|website=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|date=September 4, 2018|access-date=November 3, 2020}}</ref><ref name="YG">{{cite web|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/young-gun-folarin-balogun|title=Young Gun: Folarin Balogun|publisher=Arsenal F.C.|date=July 12, 2018|access-date=March 29, 2019}}</ref> Before trialling with Arsenal, he had trialled with North London rivals [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and nearly signed for them.<ref name="YG" />

In 2017, he was an integral part of [[Trevor Bumstead]]'s [[Arsenal F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Arsenal U16]] side that won the [[Liam Brady]] Cup, beating [[Bayern Munich Junior Team|Bayern Munich]], [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|Manchester United]] and [[Juventus FC Youth Sector|Juventus]] respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/20170403/under-16s-lift-liam-brady-cup|title=Under-16s lift Liam Brady cup|publisher=Arsenal F.C.|date=April 3, 2017|access-date=February 7, 2023}}</ref>

He signed a professional contract in February 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pulse.ng/sports/football/folarin-balogun-of-nigerian-descent-signs-professional-contract-with-arsenal/phb0e9z|title=Nigerian born Folarin Balogun signs professional contract with Arsenal|first=Tosin|last=Abayomi|date=February 14, 2019|access-date=March 29, 2019|newspaper=[[Pulse Nigeria]]}}</ref> In July 2020, after failing to agree a new contract with Arsenal, he was linked with a transfer away from the club, including a proposed £8 million move to [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/07/03/folarin-balogun-appears-confirm-arsenal-exit-instagram-failing-agree-new-contract-12940127/|title=Folarin Balogun appears to confirm Arsenal decision on Instagram|newspaper=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|publisher=[[DMG Media]]|date=July 3, 2020|access-date=November 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11670/12040157/folarin-balogun-arsenal-demand-8m-for-brentford-target|title=Folarin Balogun: Arsenal demand £8m for Brentford target|first=Lyall|last=Thomas|website=[[Sky Sports]]|date=July 31, 2020|access-date=November 3, 2020}}</ref>

==== 2020–22: Senior team debut and loan to Middlesbrough ====
On October 29, 2020, he made his senior debut in the [[2020–21 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]], coming on as a substitute in the 74th minute, in a group stage match against [[Dundalk F.C.|Dundalk]].<ref name="auto3">{{cite web|url=https://www.football.london/arsenal-fc/players/balogun-arsenal-debut-dundalk-win-19190423|title='Better than Firmino!' – Arsenal fans go nuts after Mikel Arteta's Folarin Balogun decision|first=George|last=Smith|website=[[Football.london]]|date=October 29, 2020|access-date=November 3, 2020}}</ref><ref name="2020-21" /> On November 26, he scored his first senior goal, in a Europa League group stage match against [[Molde FK|Molde]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/55071648|title=Molde 0-3 Arsenal: Nicolas Pepe praised by Mikel Arteta|website=BBC Sport|date=November 26, 2020|access-date=November 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name="2020-21" />

On April 26, 2021, Balogun signed a new long-term contract with the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/folarin-balogun-signs-new-long-term-contract|title=Folarin Balogun signs new long-term contract|publisher=Arsenal F.C.|date=April 26, 2021|access-date=April 26, 2021}}</ref> On August 13, Balogun made his [[Premier League]] debut in a 2–0 loss against newly promoted [[Brentford F.C|Brentford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4202750/2021/08/13/folarin-balogun-starts-his-first-premier-league-game-for-arsenal-vs-brentford/|title=Folarin Balogun starts his first Premier League game for Arsenal vs Brentford|first=Art|last=de Roché|publisher=[[The Athletic]]|date=August 13, 2021|access-date=August 13, 2021}}</ref>
[[File:Arsenal v Everton - 52222904853 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Balogun training with [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in 2022]]
On January 12, 2022, he joined [[EFL Championship]] club [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] on a loan deal until the end of the season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/59966748|title=Arsenal loan striker Balogun to Boro|website=BBC Sport|date=January 12, 2022|access-date=January 12, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/folarin-balogun-joins-middlesbrough-loan|title=Folarin Balogun joins Middlesbrough on loan|publisher=Arsenal F.C.|date=January 12, 2022|access-date=January 12, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mfc.co.uk/news/folarin-balogun-joins-boro-on-loan|title=Folarin Balogun Joins Boro On Loan|publisher=Middlesbrough F.C.|date=January 12, 2022|access-date=January 12, 2022}}</ref> On March 8, he scored his first goal for ''Boro'' in a 4–1 loss to [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59787646|title=Sheffield United 4-1 Middlesbrough: Chris Wilder's return to Bramall Lane ends in heavy defeat|website=BBC Sport|date=March 8, 2022|access-date=May 31, 2025}}</ref> and later scored in back-to-back wins over [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] and [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60656890|title=Birmingham City 0-2 Middlesbrough: Boro move back into top six with routine win|website=BBC Sport|date=March 15, 2022|access-date=May 31, 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60883486|title=Peterborough United 0-4 Middlesbrough: Boro win boosts play-off hopes|website=BBC Sport|date=April 2, 2022|access-date=May 31, 2025}}</ref>

==== 2022–23: Loan to Reims ====
In August 2022, he moved on loan to French club [[Stade de Reims|Reims]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/folarin-balogun-joins-stade-de-reims-loan|title=Folarin Balogun joins Stade de Reims on loan|publisher=Arsenal F.C.|date=August 3, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/arsenal-transfer-news-balogun-reims-loan-b1016474.html|title=Arsenal confirm exit as clear-out continues but striker will be back|first=George|last=Flood|date=August 3, 2022|website=Evening Standard}}</ref> Balogun scored on his debut for the club on August 7, a 4–1 defeat to [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]]; fellow Arsenal loanee [[Nuno Tavares]], also on his debut, scored for Marseille in the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.90min.com/posts/marseille-4-1-reims-arsenal-loanees-nuno-tavares-folarin-balogun-grab-debut-goals|title=Marseille 4-1 Reims: Arsenal loanees Nuno Tavares & Folarin Balogun grab debut goals|website=90min|date=August 7, 2022|access-date=January 31, 2023}}</ref> On January 29, 2023, Balogun scored a late goal in stoppage time to seal a 1–1 draw away to league leaders [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]].<ref name=PSGgoal>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64448519|title=Paris Saint Germain 1-1 Reims|website=BBC Sport|date=January 29, 2023|access-date=January 31, 2023}}</ref> It was his eleventh goal in Ligue 1 during the [[2022–23 Ligue 1|season]], the most of any player aged 21 or under in [[Big Five (association football)|Europe's top five leagues]].<ref name=PSGgoal /> Three days later, Balogun scored his first senior hat-trick in a 4–2 win over [[FC Lorient|Lorient]], his fourteenth goal of the season in Ligue 1.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stroud|first=James|url=https://www.givemesport.com/88111409-folarin-balogun-arsenal-loanee-scores-superb-hat-trick-in-reims-v-lorient|title=FolarinBalogun: Arsenal loanee scores superb hat-trick in Reims v Lorient|website=GiveMeSport|date=February 1, 2023|access-date=February 1, 2023}}</ref> This made him the top scorer in Ligue 1 at that time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/64515741|title='Arsenal's headache' - the youngster outscoring Mbappe|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He finished the season with 21 goals, to be the fourth top scorer in the league.<ref name=":0">{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/usmnt-folarin-balogun-21st-ligue-1-goal-reims/bltf84ad71c876069be |title=USMNT hopeful Folarin Balogun scores 21st Ligue 1 goal for Reims in final game of season |publisher=Goal.com |date=June 3, 2023 }}</ref>

Upon his return to Arsenal for the 2023–24 season, Balogun stated he would not leave the club again on loan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/articles/c7211lvjk87o|title=Arsenal: 'I definitely won't go on loan again' - Folarin Balogun|date=June 19, 2023|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> In August 2023, he was reported to have attracted interest from [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], [[Inter Milan]], and [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66598324|title=Chelsea, Inter and Monaco enquire about Balogun|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

=== Monaco ===
[[File:Balogun asse asm 2425.png|thumb|upright|Balogun with [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] in 2025]]
On August 30, 2023, Ligue 1 side [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] announced the signing of Balogun on a five-year contract,<ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |date=August 30, 2023 |title=Folarin Balogun is Monegasque! |url=https://www.asmonaco.com/en/folarin-balogun-is-a-monegasque/ |access-date= |publisher=AS Monaco |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66664738|title=Monaco sign Balogun for £35m from Arsenal|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> for a reported fee of €30 million, which could rise to €40 million with add-ons.<ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |date=August 30, 2023 |title=Folarin Balogun é reforço do AS Monaco por 30 milhões de euros |trans-title=Folarin Balogun is AS Monaco's reinforcement for 30 million euros |url=https://bolanarede.pt/especial-bola-na-rede/ultima-hora/folarin-balogun-e-reforco-do-as-monaco-por-30-milhoes-de-euros/ |access-date= |website=Bola na Rede |language=pt-PT}}</ref> On September 2, he played his first match for Monaco, coming on against [[RC Lens|Lens]]. During the match, he picked up his first yellow card for simulation after trying to win a penalty.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Monaco cruise to victory against Lens |url=https://www.ligue1.com/Articles/Match-Reports/2023/09/02/monaco-cruise-to-victory-against-lens-golovin-minamino-balogun |access-date=September 3, 2023 |website=Ligue1 COM |language=en}}</ref> On September 17, he scored his first league goal for Monaco, three minutes after coming off the bench in a 2–2 draw to [[FC Lorient|Lorient]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=September 17, 2023 |title=WATCH: USMNT star Folarin Balogun scores first goal for Monaco within three minutes of stepping off the bench against Lorient {{!}} Goal.com |url=https://www.goal.com/en/lists/watch-usmnt-star-folarin-balogun-scores-first-goal-monaco-lorient/bltc0059e89b795b01b |access-date=September 17, 2023 |website=www.goal.com |language=en}}</ref> On September 22, he had his first start at the club, in which he missed two penalties in a 1–0 defeat against [[OGC Nice|Nice]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en/lists/usmnt-folarin-balogun-nice-penalties/bltc0f06a8c535a7951 |title=Disastrous first start for Folarin Balogun! USMNT star fails twice from penalty spot in first start as Monaco fall to Nice |publisher=Goal.com |date=September 22, 2023 }}</ref>

In the 2024–25 season, Balogun suffered a series of injuries which sidelined him most of the season. On May 3, 2025, he scored on his first start back from injury, a 3–1 win over [[AS Saint-Étienne|Saint-Étienne]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=May 3, 2025 |title=U.S. duo Balogun, Dike net 1st goals since injuries |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/44985225/usa-folarin-balogun-goal-monaco-injury |access-date=May 4, 2025 |website=ESPN.com |language=en}}</ref>

On November 4, 2025, he scored his first [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] goal, securing a 1–0 away win over [[FK Bodø/Glimt|Bodø/Glimt]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/story/_/id/46850717/usmnt-balogun-scores-first-ucl-goal-monaco-win |title=USMNT's Balogun scores first UCL goal in Monaco win |publisher=ESPN |date=November 4, 2025 }}</ref> On February 17 in the Champions League, Balogun scored a first-half brace against [[Paris Saint-Germain FC|Paris Saint-Germain]], though Monaco would ultimately lose 2–3.<ref>{{Cite web |title=USA's Folarin Balogun Scores First-Half Brace Against PSG In Champions League |url=https://www.foxsports.com/stories/soccer/usas-folarin-balogun-scores-first-half-brace-against-psg-champions-league |access-date=April 10, 2026 |website=www.foxsports.com |language=en-US}}</ref> One month later on March 6, he recorded another goal and assist against PSG, with Monaco winning 3–1 in the league matchup.<ref>{{Cite web |title=PSG 1-3 Monaco (Mar 6, 2026) Game Analysis |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/746635 |access-date=April 10, 2026 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref> Dating back to February 21, Balogun achieved scoring 8 consecutive league goals in a row (including 10 goal contributions in his last 10 club games) on April 19, in the 2–2 draw to [[AJ Auxerre|Auxerre]], which was tied as the 2025–26 [[Big Five (association football)|top five European league]] season record goalscoring streak shared only by [[Kylian Mbappé]] at [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] (8 goals).<ref name=":2">{{Cite web |title=Folarin Balogun is the Bang & Olufsen MVP of the AS Monaco season! {{!}} AS Monaco |url=https://www.asmonaco.com/en/news/folarin-balogun-elu-mvp-de-la-saison-de-l-as-monaco-by-bang-olufsen#:~:text=AS%20Monaco%20App-,Folarin%20Balogun%20is%20the%20Bang%20&%20Olufsen%20MVP%20of%20the%20AS,Bang%20&%20Olufsen%20by%20Monaco%20supporters. |access-date=May 30, 2026 |website=www.asmonaco.com}}</ref> Balogun's streak was also one goal away from the 21st-century Ligue 1 goalscoring streak record.<ref>{{Cite web |date=April 19, 2026 |title=Balogun continues Monaco scoring streak, Rennes boost Champions League hopes |url=https://www.rfi.fr/en/sports/20260419-balogun-continues-monaco-scoring-streak-rennes-boost-champions-league-hopes |access-date=April 19, 2026 |website=RFI |language=en}}</ref> 

Balogun finished the [[2025–26 AS Monaco FC season|2025–26 season]] as Monaco's top scorer with 19 goals and 4 assists in all competitions, and the league's fourth top scorer with 13 goals.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ligue 1 McDonald's Standings undefined/NaN - French Championship |url=https://ligue1.com/en/competitions/ligue1mcdonalds/standings?ranking=scorers |access-date=May 24, 2026 |website=Ligue 1 |language=en}}</ref> For his season performances, he was named the 2025–26 Monaco Player of the Season.<ref name=":2" />

==International career==
[[File:Folarin Balogun USMNT v Belgium Mar 28 2026-109.jpg|thumb|upright|Balogun in 2026]]
Born in the United States to Nigerian parents,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Okeleji |first1=Oluwashina |title=Nigeria yet to approach Arsenal's Folarin Balogun |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/47651821 |access-date=November 3, 2020 |website=BBC Sport |date=March 21, 2019}}</ref> and raised in the United Kingdom, Balogun was eligible to represent the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]], [[England national football team|England]], and [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] at international level before he committed himself to the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/may/25/folarin-balogun-chose-the-us-over-england-he-may-have-created-a-2026-contender|title=Folarin Balogun chose the US over England. He may have created a 2026 contender|first=Eric|last=Wynalda|date=May 25, 2023|via=The Guardian}}</ref>

=== Youth career ===
After playing for England at the [[England national under-17 football team|under-17]] level, and appearing in the [[2018 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44163466|title=European Under-17 Championships: England lose 6–5 on penalties to Netherlands|date=May 17, 2018|website=BBC Sport|access-date=April 20, 2021}}</ref> he accepted a call up from the [[United States men's national under-18 soccer team|United States under-18 national team]] in August 2018 for a training camp and a tournament in the Czech Republic.<ref name="ESPN2018" /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Emmanuel |first1=Ifeanyi |title=Arsenal's Nigerian Whizkid Provisionally Cap-Tied To England Selected To Represent USA |url=https://www.allnigeriasoccer.com/read_news.php?nid=28965 |publisher=All Nigeria soccer |access-date=November 3, 2020 |date=August 20, 2018}}</ref> He played in all four of the United States' games in the [[Václav Ježek]] Youth Tournament and scored twice.<ref name="usmnt-18">{{cite web|url=https://sbisoccer.com/2018/08/u-s-u-18-mens-national-team-wins-vaclav-jezek-tournament|title=USMNT U-18s win Vaclav Jezek Tournament|first=Larry|last=Henry Jr.|publisher=SBI Soccer|date=August 25, 2018|access-date=February 17, 2021}}</ref> He also expressed interest in playing for [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]], although he stated that he enjoys England's "style of play" which is "similar to Arsenal's".<ref>{{cite web |title='Don't Play For Nigeria' – English FA To Meet With Parents Of Arsenal Nigeria U20 Target Folarin Balogun |url=https://www.owngoalnigeria.com/2019/03/23/dont-play-for-nigeria-english-fa-to-meet-with-parents-of-arsenal-nigeria-u20-target-folarin-balogun/ |website=Own Goal Nigeria |access-date=November 3, 2020 |date=March 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Young Gun: Folarin Balogun|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/young-gun-folarin-balogun-0|access-date=January 3, 2021|publisher=Arsenal F.C.|language=en}}</ref>

In 2019, he appeared and scored for the [[England national under-18 football team|England under-18 national team]] in a tournament in Dubai.<ref>{{cite web |title=The young lions were victorious in their opening game in Dubai with a 4–1 over Japan |url=https://www.thefa.com/news/2019/mar/20/england-u18s-4-1-japan-report-200319 |website=The FA |publisher=[[The Football Association]] |access-date=November 3, 2020 |date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> In October 2020, he made an appearance for the [[England national under-20 football team|England under-20]] against [[Wales national under-20 football team|Wales]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Two quickfire goals in the first half seal win for Lee Carsley's Young Lions at SGP |url=https://www.thefa.com/news/2020/oct/13/england-mu20s-wales-report-131020 |publisher=The Football Association |access-date=November 3, 2020 |date=October 13, 2020}}</ref>

On August 27, 2021, Balogun received his first call up to the [[England national under-21 football team|England under-21 team]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Harvey Elliott: Liverpool winger receives first England U21 call-up for September internationals|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/16261/12391902/harvey-elliott-liverpool-winger-receives-first-england-u21-call-up-for-september-internationals|access-date=August 27, 2021|website=Sky Sports|language=en}}</ref> On September 7, 2021, he made his England U21 debut as a substitute during the 2–0 [[2023 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification]] win over [[Kosovo national under-21 football team|Kosovo under-21s]] at [[Stadium MK]].<ref>{{cite news|title=England U21 2–0 Kosovo U21|website=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/58460993|date=September 7, 2021|access-date=September 7, 2021}}</ref>

In October 2022, he said he was open to playing for [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/africa/63374817|title=England U21 star Balogun open to Nigeria call-up|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

=== Senior career ===
On May 16, 2023, [[FIFA]] approved Balogun's application for a switch to represent the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]]. He had been recruited by the United States through several meetings, which included watching the [[Orlando Magic]] and [[New York Knicks]] play in Florida.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tannenwald |first=Jonathan |date=May 16, 2023 |title=Highly rated striker Folarin Balogun commits to the USMNT |url=https://www.inquirer.com/soccer/folarin-balogun-usmnt-reims-arsenal-england-20230516.html |work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]] |access-date=May 16, 2023}}</ref> Balogun received his first call up to the United States senior squad on June 1, featuring in the squad for the [[2023 CONCACAF Nations League Finals]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2023/06/callaghan-selects-24-player-biosteel-usmnt-training-camp-roster-ahead-of-concacaf-nations-league |title=24 player biosteel USMNT training camp roster |website=ussoccer.com|access-date=June 1, 2023|date=June 1, 2023}}</ref> On June 18, Balogun scored his first goal for the United States in their Nations League [[2023 CONCACAF Nations League final|final]] victory over [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/articles/c72r90y5dvgo|title=Arsenal: Folarin Balogun future will be 'subject of intense debate'|date=June 19, 2023|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

Balogun was selected to the USMNT's roster at the [[2024 Copa America]]. In the first match, Balogun scored the United States' second goal in a 2–0 win against [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia]],<ref>{{cite web |title=USA's 'selfless leader' Pulisic inspires win over Bolivia |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/40417439/copa-america-2024-usa-christian-pulisic-leader-bolivia |website=ESPN |access-date=June 23, 2024}}</ref> and in the second, he scored the opener in the 2–1 defeat at the hands of [[Panama national football team|Panama]] when the U.S. was down to 10 players after a red card given to [[Timothy Weah]] in the 18th minute. Despite the loss, Balogun was awarded the Man of the Match award.<ref>{{Cite web |date=June 28, 2024 |title=Player ratings: Weah's red card costs USMNT despite Balogun's sublime goal |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/40445847/player-ratings-tim-weah-red-sets-usmnt-back-folarin-balogun-effort |access-date=June 29, 2024 |website=ESPN.com |language=en}}</ref> Following the game, Balogun, along with teammates Weah, [[Chris Richards (soccer)|Chris Richards]] and [[Weston McKennie]], suffered [[Racism in association football|racial abuse]] from online trolls. Balogun's club [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]], as well as [[CONCACAF]], [[CONMEBOL]] and the [[United States Soccer Federation|U.S. Soccer Federation]] condemned the actions and fully supported the players.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Copa America: USA 1-2 Panama - Timothy Weah suffers racist abuse after red card |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c844jrxewv8t |website=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=June 28, 2024 |title=USA soccer condemns racism after Folarin Balogun shared abuse he received on social media following USMNT loss |url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/news/usa-soccer-condemns-racism-after-folarin-balogun-shared-abuse-he-received-on-social-media-following-usmnt-loss/ |access-date=June 29, 2024 |website=CBSSports.com |language=en}}</ref> The US was eliminated after losing to [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] 1–0 in Kansas City.

==Style of play==
[[File:2023 MLS All Star Game 2023-07-19 Folarin Balogun Tim Parker.jpg|thumb|Balogun (left) playing for [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] at the [[2023 MLS All-Star Game]]]]
Balogun is known for his pace, technique, and being [[Footedness|two-footed]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=October 30, 2020 |title='This young boy is fire' - Everything you need to know about Folarin Balogun |url=https://www.planetfootball.com/quick-reads/this-young-boy-is-fire-everything-you-need-to-know-about-folarin-balogun/ |access-date=June 2, 2022 |website=Planet Football |language=en-US}}</ref> Labelled a pure "[[Squad number (association football)|number nine]]" or [[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|center forward]], Balogun has also played as a ''[[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|trequartista]]'' in youth soccer, and was deployed by [[Chris Wilder]] in a [[Forward (association football)#Second striker|second-striker]] role at [[Middlesbrough F.C|Middlesbrough]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=April 4, 2023 |title=Thriving in Transition: A Scouting Report on Folarin Balogun |url=https://theanalyst.com/2023/04/folarin-balogun-scouting-report/ |access-date=July 15, 2023 |website=The Analyst |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=April 1, 2022 |title=Folarin Balogun's Middlesbrough spell is giving Arteta food for thought at Arsenal |url=https://talksport.com/football/1076516/folarin-balogun-middlesbrough-stats-arsenal-mikel-arteta/ |access-date=July 15, 2023 |website=talkSPORT |language=en-gb}}</ref> [[Martin Keown]] compared Balogun to Arsenal's second highest ever goalscorer [[Ian Wright]], due to his pace and intelligent movement.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Wheatley|first=Chris|date=December 11, 2020|title=Arsenal's 'next Ian Wright' who has shown Arteta what he can do in 60 minutes|url=https://www.football.london/arsenal-fc/news/arsenals-next-ian-wright-who-19438307|access-date=February 15, 2021|website=Football.London|language=en}}</ref>

